0:12:46,0 --> 0:12:50,367
I'll also tell you a little bit about the physiology.


209
0:12:50,367 --> 0:12:56,2
So, one of the first changes that occurs when Rhizobium meet a plant,


210
0:12:56,2 --> 0:12:59,133
is that the root hairs, which are ordinarily straight,


211
0:12:59,133 --> 0:13:3,433
and here's an example of a fairly normal-looking root hair right here...


212
0:13:3,433 --> 0:13:7,333
instead, root hairs grow in a way that's deformed.


213
0:13:7,333 --> 0:13:10,567
Now don't think of this as root hairs curling.


214
0:13:10,567 --> 0:13:12,3
Plant cells don't curve.


215
0:13:12,3 --> 0:13:17,6
Think of a plant cell as a balloon inflated really hard inside a box.


216
0:13:17,6 --> 0:13:21,833
Plant cells don't curl, but they can grow so that they form a curl,


217
0:13:21,833 --> 0:13:23,467
and that's what happens here.


218
0:13:23,467 --> 0:13:26,467
If you take a look at this root hair, instead of growing straight,


219
0:13:26,467 --> 0:13:29,567
it's grown so that it tops over and makes


220
0:13:29,567 --> 0:13:32,767
what's called a "shepherd's crook" or "crozier."


221
0:13:32,767 --> 0:13:35,367
In that, you can see a bacterial invasion,


222
0:13:35,367 --> 0:13:37,633
which is called an infection thread, and that's shown here


223
0:13:37,633 --> 0:13:44,433
at this highly refractile line going down through the root hair.


224
0:13:44,433 --> 0:13:49,0
Now, at the same time that invasion is occurring on the outside,


225
0:13:49,0 --> 0:13:53,3
early events are also occurring inside the plant root,


226
0:13:53,3 --> 0:13:56,9
so I want you to imagine that the plant root is going out this way.


227
0:13:56,9 --> 0:13:59,33
Now here we have an uninfected plant root,


228
0:13:59,33 --> 0:14:1,2
it's typical plant root cells,


229
0:14:1,2 --> 0:14:3,967
you can see they're very long.


230
0:14:3,967 --> 0:14:8,0
They look "empty," that's because they're mostly filled with vacuoles,


231
0:14:8,0 --> 0:14:10,5
a large vacuole.


232
0:14:10,5 --> 0:14:16,6
Plant root cells, in the cortex here, have one main job:


233
0:14:16,6 --> 0:14:19,667
That is to transport and transport and transport...


234
0:14:19,667 --> 0:14:22,467
water, ions, nutrients, and so forth.


235
0:14:22,467 --> 0:14:25,6
That's what these cells do; they don't divide.


236
0:14:25,6 --> 0:14:29,133
But if the correct Rhizobium, and this is an example of something


237
0:14:29,133 --> 0:14:32,633
that happens only if you have the right species of bacterium and plant...


238
0:14:32,633 --> 0:14:37,933
if the correct Rhizobium is infected onto that plant, you get this.


239
0:14:37,933 --> 0:14:40,733
You can see the mitotic figures happening here,


240
0:14:40,733 --> 0:14:45,4
the cells in the inner cortex of the root have begun to divide.


